His military tribuneship was spent in Syria‚⁴ where he was attached to the third legion, ‘ Gallica‚’ and employed in clerica] work connected with the accounts of the army.⁵ At this time he must have been twenty or a little older. After returning to Rome, he obtained the quaestorship, the lowest senatorial office. As the minimum age for this was twenty- five,⁶ he cannot have held it before 87. It seems most probable that his term was from J uly 1, 89, to June 30, 90. The fact that he was quaestor Caesarie indicates that he was in high favor with the emperor Domitian at this time. The lea annulis, which fixed the age at which each office might be held, also required an interval of at least a year between the first and second, and between the second and third, and of two years between the third and fourth offices.
